title: Improved Air Filter for Craftbot 2 "Advanced Upgrade Package" with Enclosure

description.text:
UPDATE Jan-5-2018: FreeCAD file is now also posted.

The included filters in the Craftbot 2 "ADVANCED UPGRADE" with Dome and Door are not going to last long and also impede airflow.

The filters used for this are "E" sized with carbon pre-filter and HEPA main filter as used by the "GermGuardian FLT4100". I recommend these.

At $10 delivered for 6 carbon pre-filters and 2 HEPA, it probably works out to $5 a year of continuous printing.

Although designed for a Craftbot, it should be usable for almost any 80mm exhaust fan where there is space.

Note the the print requires a 210mm wide bed.

Printer:

Craftbot

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2mm

Infill:

20%

Notes:

PETG works well, did not try others. Due to heat in enclosure PLA is not recommended.
Turn on "fill between walls" in Cura.
Print with fan flange down. It does not need any supports.
A 8mm "Brim" is strongly recommended.

The Craftbot dome can use some modifications:

  • To avoid 12 screws to remove and replace dome, drill out screw holes in dome with 1/4" acrylic safe drill to allow dome to slip over the screw heads. This will be plenty secure for desktop use.
  • Don't plug their provided cable into the control board. Buy a 6" Y and 1 foot extension with shrouded plugs like this, and connect the Y cable to the controller, then plug extension cable and case fan into Y. Route cables on back panel with cable clips to avoid hazards such as fan blades and motors. Coil up the provided fan cable into the dome, and plug extension cable into fan. Heatshrink the now unused and exposed Y end of their cable. Now the dome can be completely removed without taking off the back of the printer to unplug the fan or exposing 12V power.

To install:

  1. remove both fan guards. Put chrome guard on outside of dome.
  2. Attach filter holder directly to fan on inside of dome (intake side)
  3. Seat HEPA filter into box with pull tabs facing out.
  4. Place pre-filter onto velcro strips on HEPA filter
  5. Snap lid into place if desired. It is optional as the filter fits quite snugly.

To remove the dome with this filter it is necessary to rotate the dome as lifting allow the filament tube to slide between the filter housing and dome.

The filter box does not interfere with printing.
FreeCAD 0.17

I searched through the various dust collection attachments on the site and only find a few that peaked my interest so I am in the process of designing one myself. Here are the parts I have designed so far, all is currently for 1-3/4" currently as that is what I use.

v2: Added new versions, and M55 thread to attach hoses and make custom curves and attachments.

I haven't printed this yet, I am in the process of restocking some filament.

Print recommendation: Twb010 has printed a version with 0.8mm nozzle and 0.6mm layer height which resulted in some layering issues in the top half. After reviewing the issue and simulating some prints, with th angle of the spiral on the inside the top should be printed at less then a .35mm layer height. I am going to be printing a test this weekend using 0.2 or 0.3mm.

I printed out the top portion this weekend using a 0.8mm nozzle and .3mm layer height, my retraction settings were not optimized but other then that turned out well. Need to fine tune the inlet nozzle.

12-8-2017: Uploaded a new version of the bottom, removed the fins, thinned the walls slightly and expanded the base to add more room for fasteners.

12/18/2017: After printing V2 I added V3 that adds a little more clearance to fir the bottom to the top. Will be adding test videos soon!

description.text:
This Lack Stacker was created because I wanted a very strong way to stack IKEA Lack-tables without having to damage them by inserting screws or nails into them.

The model leverages the fact that the Lack's legs contain a threaded pole that is screwed into the table surface. The model will wrap around this pole and sit between the leg and the surface.

Three STLs have been provided:

  • the STL with the 60 mm high spacer allows an Anet A8-printer to comfortably fit between two stacked Lack-tables (as can be seen in the photos).
  • The STL with the 0 mm spacer can be used to just stack tables comfortably without introducing extra space (except the little bit of space introduced by S-shape of the model wrapping from the outside to the inside)
  • the STL with the 100 mm spacer is there to show that the design also works when needing more space.

This design is very customizeable! This can be done either in Thingiverse's Customizer app, or by using the SCAD-file in OpenSCAD itself.

Update 2017-11-25: Cleaned up OpenSCAD-file to:

  • Allow better preview in the Customizer app
  • Add descriptions to the settings that can be customized
  • Ensure that spacer heights lower than 20 mm did not result in an unusable model.

Supports:

Yes

Infill:

15% or higher

Notes:

I recommend printing this model on its side, since this:

a) greatly reduces the amount of supports necessary,
b) makes it print faster since most printers are faster in the X+Y directions, and
b) makes the model stronger in the 'up'-direction in which the most force might be applied, because of the orientation of the layer lines.

description.text:
A deck light I designed for my own use.

It is intended to be used with 3 and 3.5 Watt G4 LED lamps. If you use incandescent, it'll probably be too hot.

Use at your own risk, if you melt them or something, not my fault. I designed around and used Rayhoo G4 LEDs and faux finish with Modern Masters Copper and Bronze finished. Basecoat with a good primer and use a metallic to keep light from bleeding through the plastic.

I need to photo and UL a pic of a finished one.

2x M4 Sized grub screws are intended to be used to provide contact to the power wire and hold the LED in place. The Holes are designed at 3.35mm. Depending on your nozzle size, it could be possible you'd have to use an M3 sized screw for larger nozzles as the hold could print smaller than designed with the larger extrusion.
M4 x 0.7 = 3.3mm Should thread into the hole perfectly for an accurate print w/ small <.3mm nozzle
M4 x 0.75 = 3.4 mm If .7 seems too loose (it shouldn't.)

A #10 woodscrew is intended to hold the base down and the dome goes on with a partial turn.

description.text:
Designed for iPhone X with the Apple leather cover.

Why another phone dock?

The new iPhone X is a few mm taller than the previous phones, so my old printed iPhone dock didn't work anymore. After some browsing I could not find any other dock I liked. The one I liked that doesn't fit does not exist for the X and I dislike mods on STLs/OBJs. The generic ones are typically clumsy or have other issues.
So I decided to design one quickly from scratch. Here's the result I would like to share.
I think there are not enough phone docks out there yet! :-)

Assembly

You need a standard apple lightning cable, that works for sure. Others are unclear, I have read the Amazon essentials lightning cables might work as well. The plugs plastic part needs to have the same oval shape, diameter and length.

  1. Put the lightning plug through the larger hole from the bottom to the top, then pull it sideways and push the plug into the smaller hole, ideally with flat pliers. If you are perfectionist protect the metal plug with some tape to not scratch it with the pliers.
    It's a very tight fit by fractions of 10ths of mm. Possibly you need to work on the hole a little bit with sandpaper or a file. The tight fit is important that the plug is not pulled out if you take the phone off the dock.
    It's by design that the plastics of the plug stand out for about 1mm - the Apple leather phone cover needs 1-1.5mm at the bottom and if it didn't stand out there was no connection of the plug.
  2. Put the cable into the cable guide at the bottom. Also very tight fit, you might need your fingernails to press it in.
  3. In the end you can push the "plug" into the larger hole for nicer optics. Use it print bottom down so that the surface is equal to the rest and not the shiny surface top. You might need to clean the "elephant foot" from the printing so that it goes in nicely.

Print parameters

The fit surely depends on print parameters and material, try slightly less extrusion / flow if you can't get it in.
I recommend to print with 0.4 nozzle and with 0.1mm layer height, everything else might change the measurements of the holes too much.

And don't forget to post a photo of your make! :-)

UPDATE 17 Dec 2017:
Upon user request I have added a version "iPhone_X_Dock_Lightning3mm.stl" where the Lightning plug stands out 3mm at the top instead of 1mm (depth of the plug cutout 9.2mm instead of 11.3mm).
That's intended for phone cases that add more at the bottom of the phone, like the Tech21 case.

UPDATE 15 February 2018:
Upon user request I have added a version "iPhone_X_Dock_NoCase.stl" for iPhone X "naked" without case.
The back wall of the rest is moved 1.5mm to the front / to the connector and the connector vertical depth is 12.2mm, that should place the plastic part even with the top of the hole. Have just measured the change and not tested it by printing it, please let me know if it needs correction.

description.text:
Introducing the RetroSteeper, a steeper for liquids and many other things. I wanted a oldie industrial sturdy design to make it appear like a cool retro machine (hence the name). You just need some M3/M8 bolts & nuts, a ~150RPM 5v/12v DC geared motor, 8x608ZZ typical skate bearings and a switch for the power supply. Feel free to implement your own electronics/enhancements. You can also take this as a start point for something else. You may think I'm crazy (and you're probably right).

Ok. You need more, see some videos here:
https://youtu.be/-lrWlsq42Vo
https://youtu.be/U7L3mhPjIZk

I started this design as an e-liquid steeper/mixer cause I am bored of steeping it manually, but it has served me well for several things, between them a mini ball tumbler for printed parts, a sauce mixer at kitchen, and even a enterprise logo oscillator jaw dropping my customers, cool!! I love it. One of the pics show a beer on top of the machine, I wasn't steeping it heheh, it shows there just for reference (sorry, I didn't had coke at hand, but same standard size.

As the motor I used draws 150mA/5v (0.75W) I use it sometimes to discharge PROTECTED batteries to take advantage of the remaining charge without wasting it, a single LiIhium ion 3000mah 18650 batt may last many hours. I am now in the process of converting it to solar energy, this way it could even work as very efective scarecrow ;-) As DC motors, its spinning speed depends on voltage, so you can change the steeping speed easily. You can even power it from USB if you choose a 5v capable geared DC motor.

The tray is modular with some holes to keep up to you how to attach things. You should attach things with an elastic chord, if you don't have one, you can print the included spiral 1m chord with ninjaflex and you are done. Machine is also modular and you can install on the upper part any other mechanism of your invention to make interesting things, or simply a cool 'RetroMachine'. As I don't know what kind of switch you will use I included plain model where you have to drill 'the old way' holes for whatever else machinery you want to attach to the main design, hence the simple cubic box design. Remember also to add some weight to the innards of the box to make it stable if you are going to put on it weighted objects. Tray holes are for metric M6 bolts, you can use them to bind together your own designs for bottles, tumblers, logos, etc. I have attached amazing things to it, trust me.

Included are reference pictures for suitable motors. It has almost no electronics, just the motor, a switch and some wires, and of course a power supply than may be even batteries or a solar cell. These motors need very little current to work. Belts are printed with ninjaflex o filaflex, don't use semiflex elastomers as these are somewhat rigid for this purpose. Easy project and awesome results, just a bunch of nuts/bolts, washers, some common bearings and a cheap motor, BOM is under $20, and even FreeCAD sources included for your convenience. Come on, build one, you won't regret !!

Pics show mine steeping one of my favourite e-liquids for vaping.

Enjoy.

TODO: Awaiting for some arduino nano's, display, RTC clock and encoder control to incorporate to the party. Maybe even some led strip, we'll see... As the base machine and gears may serve for diferent purposes without modifications (by design), I am now working on multiple top mechanisms like rotating tumblers, shake machines, mini press, plastiline extruder, a pencil sharpener, a magnet ilussion, or ball circuit with liftener...

title: Parts for 133% Ossum Jeep to fit RC 1/10

description.text:
Ok. Now you be wondering why 133%? In real life, an Army Jeep is quite small vs the general size of vehicles, so if you scale it down by 1/10, it uses 1/18 or 1/16 scale of RC parts. But RC 1/10 scale is the more common type of scale we play, more parts & choices available so you can get even higher performance, torque, grip and tires and using the more commonly M3 size of screws and nut.

Still confused? just follow the below step/instructions. haha

Step 1
First head to the original Ossum listing and download all the parts.
https://go.edwardrc.com/OssumJeep

The files you need to print from the ABOVE LINK are as follows,
NOTE 1 : always remember to apply 133% or 1.33 on the "scale" setting in your cura.
NOTE 2 : most are printed at 10% infill and 1 piece only, unless otherwise stated below

  • bumper_front.stl
  • bumper_rear.stl
  • dashboard_et_al.stl
  • fender_left.stl
  • fender_right.stl
  • front_floor_and_tub.stl
  • grill.stl
  • handle_side.stl (2x)
  • headlamp.stl (2x in transparent filament)
  • hitch.stl
  • hood.stl
  • leaf_thin.stl (4x at 50% infill has the right flex for my weight)
  • rail_front_left.stl (100% infill)
  • rail_front_right.stl (100% infill)
  • rail_rear_left.stl (100% infill)
  • rail_rear_right.stl (100% infill)
  • rear_floor
  • rear_handle.stl (2x)
  • seat_frame_left.stl (2x) then pair with right frame during assembly
  • seat_frame_right.stl (2x)
  • servo_and_Shock_supports.stl (you will need to cut the middle bridge of this)
  • shackle_a.stl (4x)
  • shackle_b.stl (4x)
  • suspension_bracket.stl (4x)
  • tailgate.stl
  • tub_wall_rear_left.stl
  • tub_wall_rear_right.stl
  • windscreen_frame.stl
  • windscreen_insert.stl
  • last part. Tip me cause I've figured out all above for you haha just kidding. Just share the photos here and in the fb group after you've printed.

Step 2

Now download and print the parts I uploaded here, which will make these 133% parts of Ossum to work with your RC 1/10 parts.
*Print as it is, do not scale up any

Step 3

As for the 4 wheels, you can print from the below link, just the Wheels/Rim, 4 of them.
https://go.edwardrc.com/2mjUsBL

Then, print this Ring when you use aftermarket Tires. The one that fits well for me as link below.
https://go.edwardrc.com/2DiRjKq

Step 4

1/10 parts to use/buy. Link below,

HG Axle Rear (affordable)

title: Flash Cold Shoe Foot for Speedlite and Yongnuo Flashes

description.text:
A friend approached me a while back with a problem. He's a professional photographer and often uses several remote flashes to light different parts of an architectural scene. The Yongnuo and Speedlite flashes he uses each come with a foot that snaps on the flash to allow it to stand on its own. The problem is that the foot is only large enough to support the flash. Once you add light modifiers to the flash, it's often too top-heavy to stand on its own.

This is a larger foot (about double the size) to allow the flash to stand safely at any angle with light modifiers attached.

He calls it "BigFoot" which is a fitting name.

See the photos for a size comparison to the original Yongnuo foot.

Notes:

Support is required to print the overhangs of the cold shoe mount. I recommend PETG over ABS for this part because the strength of the cold shoe mount depends on strong layer adhesion. The part is designed with long, curved filament paths to try to carry the stress away from the mount point, but it's still a challenge for FFF (FDM) prints to handle the focused stresses on the mount point.

I used eSun PETG filament, and it worked well:

eSun Black PETG Filament, 1.75mm (Amazon*): http://amzn.to/2xib6H0

Be very gentle when removing support material from the cold shoe mount. It's easy to crack the lips of the mount and seriously weaken the shoe. Default support material generated by Simplify3D comes out with some persuasion.

These thing files are the mounts I designed for limit switches on the GarageWorX CNC kit. I built them for my 4x4 model. I know the gantry layout is different on the smaller units, so the X-axis mounts may not work on the other sizes. The Y and Z mounts should though.

You'll need one each of the Y-axis mounts, one each of the Z's, and then 2 of the X-axis mounts. They are identical from side to side.

To mount the X's, take out two of the 1/2" 10-24 screws that mount the gantry cross and rail, replace them with a 3/4 or 1" screw and install them backwards so the threads face outward. Slide on the printed mount and then add one more 10-24 nut to secure the limit switch mount. For these switches, I used a set of smaller lever switches. Here is a link to them on Amazon: https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B00MFRMFS6

For the Y and Z switches, I used the switches that I got from Xylotex. They are the common V-156-1C25 type. Here is a link to a set on Amazon: https://www.amazon.com/dp/B01G3FCH56

To mount the Y axis brackets, Slide the printed mount over the front and rear C-channel frames, line them up so the vertical gantry plate will strike the roller, and then add a glob of hot glue to each of the clip 'legs' to keep them from vibrating loose.

The Upper Z axis mount is pretty straightforward. To mount the lower Z, remove the bottom two 1/2" 10-24 screws that secure the Z slider rail plate to the front of the Z-box. Replace them with 3/4 or 1" 10-24 screws just like on the X-axis mounts. Slide the printed mount in there - it's a close fit, so you have to angle it in there and then line it up with the screws. Then secure the printed mount onto the longer screws with one extra nut per side.

All of the small screws that attach the switches to the printed mounts are 4-40 by 3/4" machine screws and nuts. I had to trim the middle screws on the two Z-axis mounts by about 1/8 of an inch so they wouldn't touch the lead screw. The others don't need to be trimmed, but can be to avoid snagging your hand when you're working around the machine.

The lower Z and both Y mounts should be printed with supports. There is no need for supports on the upper Z or the X's.

title: Rugged iPhone8 Case
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
Rugged hard case for iPhone8. For printing with hard plastic.

So, not crazy rugged, but there's two main features that make this more robust than a typical store bought case the first is the screen is inset into the case deeper than typical. There is about 1mm of plastic raised above the screen. As in, if your phone belly flops on its face there is ample plastic keeping the ground away from the screen. (The inspiration for this project is I keep braking my phone screens!!).

The other feature is the thickness of material around the perimeter is pretty thick 3mm as in if you drop your phone on the corner there is 3mm of malleable plastic to absorb the hit.

I went through 5 print iterations adjusting the fit and phone pop in details it's pretty dialed but FYI the fit is pretty critical especially regarding the buttons so make sure you have your printer dialed in and throw your best settings at it.

If you print this, FYI, the fit is pretty tight popping the phone in and out. (this is because the case is pretty stiff and the fit is secure) Drop the mute switch on the left in first, then push the phone to the top of the case, and then the bottom of the phone pop's in pretty easy. Word of warning it will squeeze both left and right buttons when installing the phone which activates the "sos" protocol. Just 'x-out' when that pop's up on the screen to avoid accidentally calling the police or something. Then when removing the phone, pop the bottom out first then slide the phone downward out of the case once the bottom is free.

I printed this with PLA. Works great.

Also I did a bit of filing and sanding to smooth the rough edges and printing artifacts.

The buttons are separate pieces. They are "loose" buttons. You need 3 of them, it's the same button in all 3 locations. Do some detail filing if necessary to make sure the buttons move freely in the button cavities.

The spacing and fit of the buttons is critical. I recommend using super dense supports, and generally speaking throw your best print settings at this to get a good result.

Print the exterior shell super slow. I recommend 25 mm/s. This is because the little detents around the perimeter of the case are pretty jerky so you need to go super slow be be accurate and get a clean print.

description.text:
If you found this useful feel free to drop me a tip.

I was getting tired of loading my many shells with a "speed loader" and I already had an Odin M4 loader that I really loved. I tried using a "universal" adapter I found online but I found it really cumbersome because I had to hold the shell, the loader and then turn the crank. So I set off and developed this simple adapter.

You will need a screw to keep the sliding piece in the adapter, any m4 screw or something that size should fit.

You can print it in the orientation that the STL file is in. you will only require supports for the base when it prints, should be fine without supports for the rest.

title: CR-10S/Ender 2 Filament Spool Holder REMIX
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Original Text:
I loved the design/concept of the spool holder designed by edgarp (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2431355), but found the edges very hard to grab when trying to take the holder off of the filament spool. Using the dimensions on their page I remixed it with the following changes:

  • Added 5 mm of flat space on the end of both nut and base.
  • Added notches in edge for easier grip
  • Increased the overall length of the base piece by 6.5 mm to better fit the size of my CR-10S spool holder (32 mm diameter and 82 mm length to threads). This allows the stock spool holder nut to secure this addition in to place.

Please Note: With the increased length of the base both the stock CR-10 spool holder nut and the nut of this piece cannot be tightened as tight as possible. One needs to be slightly loose to allow the spool to spin freely.

If you have any comments or suggestions please let me know!

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hiJpWQYig1U

Update 1: Added STL for Ender 2 spool holder. The only changes from the CR-10s spool holder is decreasing the length to 78 mm from 82.5 mm. The nut is the same for both spool holders, only the base will change.

Update 2: Added STL (BaseV3-with-internal-nut.stl) for new and improved spool holder base that works with both CR-10S and Ender 2. This version includes internal threads that replace the stock spool holder nut so you no longer need to use the stock nut to secure the base onto the Creality spool holder. The length of the new base is 81 mm.

Print Settings!

  • You MUST use supports to print all of these parts, it was really unavoidable.
  • If you wish to back-drive this, you'll need to use at least -.05 horizontal expansion setting

This Looks Familiar!

  • This gearbox is the same size as the ones used in my first robotic arm project!
  • I have never tested it in that project, and there isn't even a sun gear with the right size hole for a NEMA 17 motor, but someday I will get to that.

Assembly

  • Assembly instructions for a very similar gearbox can be found here: https://youtu.be/1DNgqtoJMdk?t=29m13s
  • Aligning the gears with the marks is super important!
  • Placing the gears face up on a table, sort the planet gears in order (1-4) as shown in the main picture and video, insert sun gears, wrap the planets around the sun gears in the correct order, Snap Ring gear #1 on.
  • Align all gears with the marks as shown in the video, then put the rest of the ring gears on.
    You will need to close the gap in the rings before you spin this gearset or else it could skip teeth and get out of alignment, for this i have included the ring closures, that fits over all the rings
How it works

  • Ring Gears #1 & #3 will be at the same potential and Ring Gears #2 & (Optional #4) will be at the same potential

  • The use of Ring Gear #4, the 4 Module Planet Gears, and Sun Gear #4 is optional and used to increase the amount of torque this gearbox can transfer, as well as to decrease the amount of load on each gear, think of it like a door hinge.

description.text:
This is a wing mount clamp for a Tamiya Manta Ray or equivalent chassis, e.g., Dirt Thrasher.

I bought a chassis that was missing the part so created this! It's not the same as either the stock Manta Ray or Top Force part. The Manta Ray one was designed for self-tapping screws so the holes went quite deep, and the Top Force version includes metal inserts for machine screws for added security and to minimise the profile.

Mine has space for nuts you can use machine screws, but without needing to source the little Tamiya inserts.

I've also included parts to replace the little washers for the top side of the wing.
